-- AWB, BHP, Fortescue, Linc, Macquarie, Woodside: Australian Stock Preview
-- Shani Raja
-- 2010-08-01T22:20:15Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-08-01/awb-bhp-fortescue-linc-macquarie-woodside-australian-stock-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed on July 30. All
prices are from that close unless otherwise stated.  
 The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in September
rose 0.2 percent to 4,470 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank of
New York Australia ADR Index  declined 0.2 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  dropped 0.7 percent to 4,493.50.  
 Mining shares: A measure of metals traded in  London  rose
for a third day, gaining 1.7 percent.  
 BHP Billiton  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining company,
lost 0.8 percent to A$40.12 in Sydney. Its American depositary
receipts slipped 0.2 percent in New York trading.  Rio Tinto
Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-largest mining company, fell
1.2 percent to A$70.61 in Sydney.  
 Oil companies: Crude oil for September delivery increased
0.8 percent to settle at $78.95 a barrel on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.  
 Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
largest oil and gas producer, declined 0.3 percent to A$41.60.
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) dropped 2 percent to A$13.30.  
    AWB Ltd.  (AWB AU): Australia’s largest wheat exporter was
downgraded to “neutral” from “overweight” at JPMorgan Chase
& Co. AWB shares surged 3.7 percent to 99 Australian cents.  
      Fortescue Metals Group Ltd.  (FMG AU): Australia’s third-
biggest iron-ore producer said the government’s proposed mining
levy threatens to stop its A$17 billion ($15 billion) expansion
in Western Australia. Fortescue shares lost 1.2 percent to
A$4.29.  
      Linc Energy Ltd.  (LNC AU): Indian power company Adani Power
Ltd. will buy Queensland coal tenements from Linc Energy for A$1
billion, the Australian newspaper said, citing unidentified
sources it said were familiar with the deal. Linc shares fell
1.2 percent to A$1.595.  
   Macquarie Group Ltd.  (MQG AU) Australia’s biggest
investment bank was raised to “buy” from “neutral” by
analysts at UBS AG. Macquarie shares slumped 3.1 percent to
A$37.20.  
 To contact the reporters for this story:
